The paper deals with unsupervised network representation learning (UNRL) approaches, which involves learning representations of nodes in a graph without any supervision. This falls under the category of machine learning and artificial intelligence, which is covered by several sub-categories in arXiv CS. Specifically, the paper discusses various optimization objectives and deep architectures used for UNRL, which suggests that it could belong to cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) or cs.LG (Machine Learning). The paper also discusses the differences among these methods and their performance on downstream tasks, which could fall under cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) or cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms). Finally, the paper discusses the evaluation of UNRL methods and suggests experimental design and interpretation of results, which could fall under cs.SD (Software Engineering). Therefore, the most likely sub-categories are cs.SI and cs.LG, followed by cs.AI, cs.DS, and cs.SD.
